Prologue
"S'il vous plaît !", Eirwen the queen implored. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The King of Ice looked at his wife from the top of his throne, his royal advisor beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. He scowled at the thought.
The little girl looked very much like her mother: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue locks. The King of Ice thought that a daughter would make him look weak. After all, he had only had sons until then.
"Your only options are to kill your child or send her back to nature. That's her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat her name as if it were poison. He had done it before.
Frostwell had not always been a single kingdom. It had been split in two, North and South. To the north, the non-magical kingdom. To the south, a kingdom full of fantastical representations of power. Due to the greed of the North, the two kingdoms had torn themselves apart in an endless war, until the South proposed a truce.
The South was cornered, and their royal family would have done anything to stop the bloodbath. They proposed that their only princess become the Queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Then, the South would have allied itself with the North to form one kingdom. The North had accepted, and Princess Eirwen had married Prince Akull.
"I beg of you, my highness, in exchange for the life of my child, do whatever you want with me, imprison me, banish me, or even kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding tightly onto her child in her arms.
The King of Ice lowered his gaze at his wife, with disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he would have pity on her. The one he had lived with for twenty-two years, who had always taken care of him in his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Very well, the child will be allowed to live in the palace", he began, drawing a sigh of relief from his wife. "However", he added, "you will be executed".
The counselor and Queen Eirwen herself shared a horrified glance. She lowered her gaze slowly. "Yes, Highness", she said, bowing.
The King of Ice ordered the royal advisor to take the child to one of the vacant rooms in Eirwen. Once this was done, he commanded the guards to lead Eirwen to the execution site, where all the inhabitants of the village could attend the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the inhabitants cried out their indignation at seeing their only queen, the kindest, about to be killed. Some people were crying, others were screaming and trying to attack the guards, while others still wondered what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Free her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the person most feared in the kingdom made her entrance. The fire user. The former queen Eirwen was to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even the criminals. This was the cruelest punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was hanged on the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then the user of fire set the gallows ablaze, and a single tear rolled down the cheek of the ex-queen.
"Survive, Kari". This was the end of the reign of Queen Eirwen.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds coming from the farthest room to the left of the south wing of the palace always frozen. The assistants passing by would always wonder what was in this room, frightened of what could be found inside. The rumors of the maids danced in the corridors. It was believed that the late wife of the King of Ice, Eirwen, was in this room, waiting to be freed.
"They could not be more in error", thought Ivory as she walked towards the south wing, while the assistants went back and forth murmuring to each other. They don't know at all what's in this room.
Of course, these rumors also applied to Kari, as she was the only person authorized to enter the room.
Toc Toc. "Miss Kari, are you there?"; murmured Ivory at the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Kari wondered if she would invite her in, unlike the previous times when Kari had asked her.  I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory chuckled at the memory. Kari had thrown a book onto her shoulder, but when she realized it was her, she immediately apologized.
Only one knock came from inside, which seemed to mean she was there, but after all, where else would she be?
"Can I come in?", asked Ivory, remembering the time when she had let herself in without asking for permission.
A knock came from inside. It seemed like she was saying yes. Ivory shuddered, from cold, but also because of the noise. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a room that was supposed to be empty, even though she had been in that room for years.
"Here I am," said Ivory, slowly opening the door. The scene inside the room was unusual, according to normal people's standards, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statues were scattered about. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was also colder than the rest of the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have blown in inside.
The girl who was there was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her blanket, where she was reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern lit up the space.
"Which notebook are you reading?" asked Ivory as she sat down beside Kari on her bed.
